{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"07fbd8b6-8541-4149-a4cf-27684e751d71","content":"You can install `dotnet-trace` as a standalone tool without the SDK by downloading it directly as a self-contained binary:\n\n```bash\n# From inside the container\ncurl -sSL https://aka.ms/dotnet-trace/linux-x64 -o /tmp/dotnet-trace\nchmod +x /tmp/dotnet-trace\n```\n\nThen collect a CPU trace:\n\n```bash\n# Find your app's PID\n/tmp/dotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a CPU profile (Ctrl+C to stop)\n/tmp/dotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling -o /tmp/trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**Other options:**\n- **`dotnet tool install`** — requires the SDK, so not applicable here.\n- **`kubectl cp`** or **`docker cp`** — download `dotnet-trace` on the host, then copy it in.\n- **Sidecar container** — run a diagnostics sidecar that shares the process namespace (`shareProcessNamespace: true` in Kubernetes).\n\nTo analyze the trace, copy the `.nettrace` file out and open it in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or **Speedscope** (`dotnet-trace convert --format speedscope`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"788d63f7-b1e8-4827-84c4-d7b22dab83be","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to get `dotnet-trace` into a Linux container that doesn't have the .NET SDK installed, to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app experiencing high CPU.\n\nThis is a knowledge question about .NET diagnostics tooling. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":379,"requestId":"67C4:12FCC3:ABB1AA4:BAB2772:69FD3C92"},"id":"0c56074a-e5a6-43fb-80fa-38790cb73203","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:30:03.607Z","parentId":"2a9fe592-153a-4feb-9256-ed97aff8e8c2"}
